[A heartwarming story is always appreciated. Inviting the mothers to enter facilities adjacent to the treatment center one month before delivery is surely contributing to successful births for both the mother and newborn infant. One hopes that as there are more successful births, the stigma these babies face will diminish and eventually disappear. - Mod.LK]

- Tue 1 Oct 2019. Change of heart
UN OCHA, ReliefWeb, WHO report [abridged, edited]
https://reliefweb.int/report/democratic-republic-congo/dear-parents-and-neighbours-young-mother-tells-her-story-ebola


A young mother tells her story of Ebola denial and then gratitude for treatment
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
When 33-year-old KV first left a health facility, it was the middle of the night and she was running away.

Staff from the World Health Organization (WHO) were making arrangements to transfer her to an Ebola treatment centre and she was terrified. Fortunately for her, she ran to her neighbour, who happened to be a police officer and knew very well of her family's situation and what [she] needed if she was to survive.

She needed to be evacuated to a proper treatment facility. But [she] was refusing to go. The chief health clinic nurse who took the call from the police officer that 30 Aug 2019 night and made the arrangements remembers how [the patient] resisted "bitterly."

Although she was reluctant to go to the treatment centre, [she] now is grateful. "At the [Ebola treatment centre], much to my surprise, I was warmly received. The doctors would plead with me to eat when I had no appetite. They were really nice and hospitable. I thank them now; I regret my refusal to cooperate and do apologize to every one of them," she says as neighbours, waiting out in the road, sing and dance in celebration of her surviving.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
